#X text 267 133 By default we have a single reference point of MIDI pitch 60 (C4) and a tracking amount of 100%. This means that C4 outputs a ratio of 1 and C5 outputs an octave higher (a ratio of 2) and C3 outputs an octave below (a 0.5 ratio)!, f 50;
#X text 267 199 A tracking of 50% means that an octave higher is half an octave \, so we have a ratio that is equal to the square root of 2 and a 200% tracking gives us a ratio of 4 (2 octaves)!, f 50;
#X msg 68 193 ref 48;
#X msg 76 220 ref 48 60;
#X msg 57 165 ref 60;
#X msg 98 277 50 100;
#X text 267 251 You can change the reference point with the 'ref' message or '-ref' flag with up to 2 values. If you have 2 values like '48 60' \, then you have a range from 40 to 60 where the output is always 1! Values above 60 get tracked according to this upper reference point and values below get tracked according to the lower reference point. A single value sets both the lower and upper references., f 50;
#X listbox 151 318 10 0 0 0 - - - 0;
#X text 267 347 You can also set up to two tracking values. The first is the tracking amount below the lower reference point and the second is for above the upper reference point. A single value sets the same tracking amount for both. You can set the tracking values in the right inlet or with the -amount flag., f 50;
