#X text 188 130 By default we have a linear tracking in pitch difference. But you can use exponential factors. An exponential factor of '1' or '0' is linear and '0' is the default. Values greater than one expand the tracking amount \, where A semitone difference is much lower than higher intervals. Regardless of the exponential factor \, if you have a tracking amount of 100% \, an octave higher or lower will still be the same as linear (respectively '2' and '0.5'). Exponential values lower than 1 have the opposite behaviour. Note that below and above the reference point(s) we have a mirrored behaviour., f 74;
#X text 190 234 Hence \, they form a sort of 'S' shaped curve. The plot below is done with a [rescale] object., f 31;
#X obj 133 299 else/knob 61 0 200 0 100 empty empty #dfdfdf #7c7c7c #000000 1 0 0 0 1 320 0 0 0 empty empty 0 12 0 -15 0 1 0 0 0 0;
#X floatatom 133 378 8 0 0 0 - - - 0;
#X text 244 311 Changing the amount also affects the overall range of the curve., f 26;
#X text 445 426 You can set up to two exponential factors. Like the other parameters \, it means one is for the curve below the reference points and the other for the curve above., f 27;
#X text 35 438 You can have negative values \, which will flip the curves vertically. Try with the number box above., f 23;
